    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. that makes sense. the manual also mentioned that blockages can be a huge issue for the system. what kind of things usually cause those blockages and how do pilots check for them?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Blockages in the pitot-static system can occur due to various factors, such as insects, bird droppings, ice, or debris. These blockages can prevent air from flowing freely into the pitot tube, leading to inaccurate or zero readings on the airspeed indicator. This can be particularly dangerous during critical phases of flight, such as takeoff and landing, where accurate airspeed readings are crucial for maintaining control of the aircraft.\n\nPilots can check for blockages in the pitot-static system by visually inspecting the pitot tube and static ports for any visible obstructions. They can also use the aircraft's pitot-static heat system to melt away any ice that may be blocking the pitot tube. In some cases, pilots may also use a pitot-static heat system to warm the entire system, ensuring that all blockages are cleared.\n\nIf a pilot suspects a blockage in the pitot-static system, they should immediately notify air traffic control and follow the appropriate emergency procedures. This may involve declaring an emergency, diverting to the nearest suitable airport, and preparing for a possible forced landing. It is crucial for pilots to be aware of the potential for pitot-static system blockages and to take appropriate measures to prevent them from occurring.",
